{"title": "Nice Mice", "content": "Andrey Konchalovskiy on why he changed the Mouse King to on why he changed the Mouse King to the Rat King in his adaptation of The Nutcracker \"I cannot imagine mice as the embodiment of evil. Mice are such charming little creatures, and it is not by accident that Mickey Mouse became an absolutely universal hero.\"\n\nUnlike rats, mice are often portrayed as nice and heroic even though they are common household pests.\n\nVery small and cute, yet wild, the mouse is an animal often used as a metaphor for someone easily underestimated. Thus, mouse characters and humanoid mouse races tend to be heroic and really good people, yet easily underestimated. In many works, this last trait is something they have grown to resent deeply. It's hard to demand respect from someone when you can't even reach his knees and your voice is very squeaky \u2014 no matter how brave you are.\n\nThese mice characters are designed to be likable one way or another. Some are heroic, some are nice, and some are both.\n\nFictional mice of this sort will typically be white, tan or light gray, and are also often drawn with deliberately cute, chubby or fluffy designs, generally tending towards large eyes and short, round snouts, something particularly apparent when mice appear in the same works as rats.\n\nContrast You Dirty Rat! for rodents, specifically rats, who are portrayed as disgusting, often as the Unpleasant Animal Counterpart to mice. See also Righteous Rabbit for the lagomorph end of the spectrum.", "url": "https://tvtropes.org/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/NiceMice", "media_links": ["/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheVoyageOfTheDawnTreader", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Film/TheNutcrackerIn3D", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Theatre/TheNutcracker", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Creator/ArtSpiegelman", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/Maus", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/MouseGuard", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/ThePowerpuffGirls", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/ComicBook/SunnyvilleStories", "/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/